Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
This version is just so much better than the Disney one. Mowgli actually walks on all fours and has animalistic habits, is truly raised to believe he's a wolf, there's true danger and violence and not just a kid climbing trees and playing with ropes, he's native and with an accent as well. While the CGI is not the greatest and looks a bit too much at points the plot *definitely* makes up for it. Getting to see Mowgli in the village and learning to be man but still accepting the jungle as his home, as both being a part of him. It's magnificent.

My second time watching this movie and I was not disappointed at all. 

Except when my baby Bhoot died :((

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment: Never understood the critical hate this impressive movie received. The movie was rightfully dark about both the animal and the human worlds, especially colonialism that hunted the treasures of nature. And the good, tragic souls in both. A human boy raised by wolves, the one who doesn't belong, cannot exactly have Disney-fied fun life. It had tough truths, heartbreaks and of course the dark sadness of Bhoot's death. It was a bit clunky in places and not quite satisfying and pitch-perfect but it got most things right (including Akila's and Shere Khan's personality and the latter's defeat and final death). Maybe people used to Disney versions didn't like that the animals weren't exactly pleasant looking but they signified the jungle's ancientness and the unwelcome changes due to man (like the elephant for ex). Must watch.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
The movie takes on the contentious issues of habitat degradation and trophy hunting with a couple of strong, poignant scenes. In the beginning, you see pockets of trees and lush greenery gradually give way to human settlements, as well as the collision course between Man and beast when they are forced into close proximity. One could argue that Shere Khan is a villain created by Man's relentless encroachment.
And towards the end, the heartbreaking scene where Mowgli comes upon the head of jolly friend and fellow outlier, Bhoot, among Captain Lockwood's trophy collection - a moment of epiphany for the boy who, only a few scenes back, had considered kinship with mankind.

The characters are well fleshed and multi-dimensional: the motherly, fierce and proactive Neesha; the jolly but exacting instructor, Baalu; the sensitive but ferocious Bhageera with a scarred past;  the wise and proud leader of the wolf pack, Akeelah; and the sheer depredatory evil that is Shere Khan.

If you call it a coming-of-age movie, you wouldn't be too mistaken, for through several knocks, falls, bruises, scrapes and banishment, Mowgli grows into the half man - half wolf (yet, neither both) who becomes their leader. 
The runt of the pack who makes several fearless moves to protect his own and bring about justice - for those of mankind (his mother inclusive) killed by Khan, and those of the animal world needlessly killed and maimed by Lockwood - just as Akeelah had prophesied.
And in this prophecy lies the covert message that the survival of the animals and the jungle will depend on the man-cub (animal lingo for a more animal-loving, younger human generation).

Comment:
Almost everyone here is obsessing over how much they disliked the scene of Bhoot. Personally though, I liked that scene. Not the death specifically, of course. I‚Äôm not someone who enjoys death or anything. I just like this bold move by the creators of the movie, how the filmmakers were willing to do something different and unexpected that catches the audience off guard. There should be more of these scenes, more filmmakers who are willing to step into unconventional areas and try new things that truly surprise their audience. In movies like these, most filmmakers don‚Äôt dare to risk putting in anything too dark or different in their films (at least in the films like this that I‚Äôve watched), but these creators did, and I love that.

Also, I think everyone is overreacting about the scene. They aren‚Äôt really talking about anything else in the movie. It‚Äôs as if somehow that one scene made the whole movie terrible.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment: This movie was soo harsh, the Bhoot scene, all the blood. Back in 2016 I thought I found my definite favourite Jungle Book adaptation, guess I was wrong, Mowgli was damn amazing. I am amazed how the young lead did such a well job, I was fully immersed into the movie and happenings. But when I look at the negative comments and reviews they all almost always critic two things. Bhoot's fate and the cgi. Bhoot scene truly wasn't for the faint of heart or children, that I get but giving a movie a bad rating for a characters death (especially one which wasn't even in the book) is really stupid. CGI, I can understand. It's motion capture, not as realistic as disney but it has it's charm. I like how they made the animals which Mowgli understands more human-like and with expressions. Notice how monkeys have none of that. And one thing you should never forget. The 2016 adaptation was made by Disney, who has pretty much perfected their CGI with their budget.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
SPOILER ALERT:
I got so mad when I saw that Bhoot got stuffed. Because Bhoot was basically Mowgli's best friend. And how their last conversation before Bhoot died was Mowgli being mad, and saying mean things. (I don't blame him) Bhoot was just trying to cheer him up and saying that he belonged and he was a wolf. But at that time Mowgli was upset at Bagheera over what he did at the race. So, he was just not in the mood and didn't believe anything Bhoot said. That  hunter is just.. ü§¨ü§¨

I also didn't like when AKELA DIED. Because overall Akela was very nice. The way he died was the bad part. I honestly did NOT LIKE THE HUNTER ONE BIT. If anyone that watched the movie didn't know it's the Hunter that shot Akela. I honestly don't care if it was by accident or not, he got what he deserved. Akela didn't deserve that, Akela was trying to save Mowgli at that moment when Sheer Khan was trying to bite him. 

Sheer Khan and the hunter got what they deserved. Akela and Bhoot did not. I don't understand why they had to choose those certain characters to die. Bhoot and Akela's death made me cry. Once I saw that Bhoot was stuffed I just burst out in tears. And after I saw Akela I didn't know it was him at first. But after I saw that it was Akela I cried so hard I almost made an ocean with my tears. Overall, I guess I liked the film. By the way, if you don't know why Mowgli told the elephant that the hunter did that to it, it's because he stuffed Bhoot, and because he needed the elephants help and that was his revenge.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
After watching this movie I realized one thing: I was more emotionally invested in this movie than I was in the Disney film. 

The storyline might have stumbled here and there, but the characters were each well defined and there was amazing foreshadowing. 

The fact that the tone of the story is a bit darker is also a very delicious treat. People assume that children cannot mentally process darker stories or that they are oblivious to the happenings of the world, but children listen and children see. They may not have the vocabulary to express what they see and what they feel, but they understand. 

Thank you, Netflix, for respecting children!!

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
I like both versions. They each have their own charm.
Pros :
1. It's similar to the book coz it's dark
2. Loved the actor who plays mowgli. Convincing. 
3. The turn of events was captivating. Direction was good. 

Cons:
1. Why make it so dark? It's a children's tale for God's sake
The world isn't that bad . It's not a fairy take either. It's how u look at it.
2. The hunter and Bhoot plots were unnecessary and silly.
I did like Bhoot, but come on.
3. If you want to change the story please don't call it Mowgli.
4. Horrible CGI. I felt like it was a computer game.
5. Tigers can't be killed so easily.. They are stronger than lions, athletic, fast and intelligent 

I liked the movie but wouldn't watch it again. Would always go back to the Disney version. Be happy in life, always focus on the good parts.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment: If y‚Äôall are looking for something to watch on Netflix I recommend #Mowgli. This is one of the instances when two movies are the same in some way. Example: A Bug‚Äôs Life and Antz. Armageddon and Deep Impact. Volcano and Dante‚Äôs Peak. Olympus Has Fallen and White House Down. In 2016 they made the CGI Disney Remake of The Jungle Book. I liked that film too but felt like it was just a cash-nostalgia grab. This film is more of an adaption of the book it‚Äôs self. The darker tone makes it more intense and realistic. The voice acting is great and the kid that plays Mowgli is great. Andy Serkis Motion Capture expert from Lord of the Rings and Planet of the Apes makes his directorial debut as well as voices Baloo. I would love to see him adapt other source material as a director. Even his real life son plays a scene stealing role as an albino wolf cub named #Bhoot. Yes, there have been many adaptions of The Jungle Book. But this one will be worth the watch. 8 1/2 out of 10.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment: This movie is so much refreshing and realistic in terms of storytelling than the mushy crap Disney threw with The Jungle Book. You fall in love with the realistic feeling jungle which is not a cake-walk unlike shown in other versions. This movie has grit, sorrow, adventure, happiness and gives the true sense of Mowgli and Its legend. The Movie is far better than Disney in many ways- the most striking difference comes in Mowgli. Unlike the hyper intelligent and born-to-be-engineer Mowgli in the Jungle Book, here the Mowgli seems much more real to the book. Christian Bale, Benedict Cumberbatch, Andy Serkis and all rest of the artists have done a fantastic job to elevate the characters, especially "Little Brother" from Bagheera to Mwogli is fantastic. All in all an absolute praise worthy movie and Thank God it breaks ranks from the unreal garbage lullaby Disney produces.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
I am not a fan of The Jungle Book as a whole. Related to the Disney version or not. But, seeing a trailer for this version certainly caught my interest. I just got done watching this movie, and it is one of my favorite films of 2018! 

It is unfortunate that it will most likely be overlooked by many people because of the 2016 Jungle Book movie. Mowgli is a vastly superior film. The acting is great and I approve of the more realistic tone. Shere Khan is a fun and dark villain. Benedict sure is having fun voicing the character. Christian Bale is great as Bagheera. I admit, I got teary-eyed during one scene. That rarely happens when I watch a tv show or a movie. I highly recommend this movie!

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment: I was fortunate enough to work on this movie for the final two days of production, including one day where I and a small crew were very up-close and personal during voice recordings in De Lane Lea Studios, London. I had the pleasure of filming Andy Serkies as he worked with his children (who I believe were doing wolf cub voices, if I remember correctly). At the end of filming he shook everyone in the room's hand, but unfortunately myself and my camera were hidden behind two bright LED lights and he didn't notice me before he left. Luckily I shared an elevator ride with him earlier in the day, and I have to say he is one of the humblest, nicest men I've ever met in the film industry. Very excited to see this when it comes out, especially as there are a couple of shots in some of the trailers that I believe I was present for! It's an experience I'll definitely remember for the rest of my life.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment: If you want to challenge Disney, you can't out Disney them. The brothers Grimm, and Hans Christian Anderson's stories were all disneyfied. Tell the stories the way they were originally written and make "the way the were originally told" part of your marketing. People would come to see the movie, just to see what the differences are. Of course they would no longer be a 4 quadrant movie, but if the box office for horror is any indication, they could be extremely profitable. Most if not all of the fairytales that walt disney used were in the public domain. Very smart of him. Making films of proven literary hits. Having the talent to know which ones to use and how to adapt the medium to film. I am sure there is someone out there smart enough to do that now. Disney was also a stickler for quality. Take your time and write a great script, and get good actors. Both of those things can be accomplished without spending a lot of money.

Though I have a problem with Bagheera. It's not as much a problem with BAGHEERA, but its a problem that it is ME who has it with Bagheera. In he Polish translation that I grew up with, Bagheera is female and I admired her with all my heart, I wanted to be like her and I was so in love with her, she was my first crush (as much as a 3 year old can have a crush). I don't know if it classifies as transphobic, but I just can't see Bagheera as a male, putting aside the pronouns, I just see her as so quintessentially feminine that I just don't see any male Bagheera as Bagheera.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
I have to speak as a massive fan of The Jungle Book. EVERY ADAPTATION OF JUNGLE BOOK IS ALLOWED TO EXIST AND ALL CAN BE ENJOYED.

For some perspective, the very first adaptation of The Jungle Book was all the way back in 1942 which was a British-American classic film that starred Indian actor Sabu as Mowgli. Then the Disney animated version came along and a Soviet animated version that was darker like the book. And then we got in the 1990s live action versions from Disney and I believe one direct to video studio. Oh the 1994 version also is interesting as it started Jason Scott Lee as Mowgli with a supporting cast of British english characters including characters played by Lena Heady (Cersei Lannister) and Sam Neil (A year after he did Jurassic Park).

Then in the 2010s production began on two different Jungle Book movies: one at Disney which was more a direct adaptation of its animated film and anothrr at Warner Bros which is directed by the performance capture legend Andy Serkis. Now keep this in mind: The Disney 2016 version was definitely its own story and makes a lot of changes - more so making Mowgli a more interesting and dynamic character and changing his arc to finding his place in the world which leads to the best change aftwr he faces Shere Khan: Mowgli stays with the wolf pack and doesnt leave the jungle. While theres roots in the animated version it is very safe to say that the 2016 version was a different movie so dont just write it off immediately.

The upcoming version that is on Netflix is the same film that Andy Serkis directed for Warner Bros. People think production delayed just because of Disney but in actuality its more likely that Andy Serkis was more busy with other films - namely the Planet of the Apes films which while not a director was heavily involved creatively in those movies. That said you should be excited as Andy‚Äôs work in special effects and his input in the story of the latter Planet of the Apes films is a sign of how good his Jungle Book film will be. Characters will be multidimensional regardless if they are animals or humans.

Comment: I am so sick of people saying that this is another Disney remake. It is not. Let me explain it. The Disney movie was nothing like the book at all, (and I don‚Äôt mean that the animated Disney movie is bad because I love it, even though I also love the book) but then Andy Serkis decided that he wanted to make a version of the jungle book that was actually like the book, so he started making that in 2012. But then Disney got scared that someone was making a version of the jungle book, so they remade the animated movie and got it done before Andy Serkis got done with his. So then everyone thought that mowgli was a rip off of the Disney remake because the Disney remake came out first. So in short Disney made their remake so this film would not have a chance at being a hit. ‚ÄúWhat a noble thing to do Disney.‚Äù

I just hope early descriptions stay true, and Kaa is finally a friend again.

Title: Mowgli: Legend of the Jungle | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
Michael Espinoza
A few things...........

- First off, I like this trailer much better than the teaser. I guess that goes without saying, but it does a better job of conveying the type of story it is, as well as a better look of the world, so more people aren't left wondering why there's another jungle book movie, and more interested in just seeing for themselves.

- I've never been a huge fan of CG animals in live action, that being said, the way some of these animals look is grotesque. Using Serkis's method of taking someone's face and stretching it out to form an animal for the sake of capturing more realistic expression is nice, but it's done at the expense of making them look like part of the world. You can do this with Gollum and Snoke, because they're not real. They can be deformed as much as you want. Bears, panthers, tigers, snakes, and wolves however, are real, and they need to look believable. That's one limitation CG in live action has that animation does not.

-This film stays true to the original story. Mowgli's conflict is choosing between his man hood and his animal brethren. Shere Khan is not the main villain, but is still an antagonist and is probably Mowgli's biggest driving force. I'm also pretty interested myself to see what Tabaqui is like in this film.

- All in all, I think this film will be alright. Not anything special, because live action adaptations always have the same problem going for them, but I'm still excited.

Disney decided they wanted to make a live action version of their jungle book a little bit after and managed to get theirs finished first and released.  The Disney jungle book is not an adaptation of the original rudyard Kipling novel. Walt Disney is famous for telling his writers to throw the book out when writing the film. He wanted the characters and the setting but nothing else. Andy serkis's jungle book now called "mowgli: legend of the jungle" is an adaptation of the original novel. It's going to be darker and more violent. I think Warner bros lost faith not because of the quality of the film but because people were gonna be confused and hate the film because they thought it was the sequel to the Disney one.
